<article>

  <p>
    Something can stop. Not a mood shifting, not a thought finishing — a more
    total interruption: ordinary consciousness blanks, time seems to have a hole
    in it, and only afterward does the mind notice that a stretch was missing.
    Practitioners reach for big words. Some call it
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nirodha" data-en="cessation; ending">nirodha</span>.
    Some call it a glimpse of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation; the unconditioned">nibbāna</span>.
    Some treat it as proof that practice has finally “worked.”
  </p>

  <p>
    None of those labels is entitled by the phenomenology alone. A gap in
    experience is a conditioned event about which little can be known from the
    outside — and less than people usually claim from the inside. The useful work
    is to describe carefully, refuse premature metaphysics, and return to ordinary
    training without turning the interruption into a new center of gravity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Notes, not conclusions. Worth holding lightly.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Can Be Said Without Hype</h2>

  <p>
    Consider a sit that has grown quiet. Breath is subtle. Thought thins. Then —
    without a decision — there is no next object. No watcher reporting the blank.
    No narrative about “entering.” Later, awareness resumes as if a switch flipped
    back on: body, room, the faint shock of having been elsewhere without
    elsewhere. The mind reconstructs a story because reconstruction is what minds
    do.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sober inventory is smaller than the story. Something like a discontinuity
    occurred. Ordinary contents — sights, sounds, thoughts, the sense of continuous
    self-presence — were not available for a stretch. Fear, wonder, or craving for
    a repeat may surge afterward. None of that settles what happened in technical
    terms. Sleep, absorption fringe-states, neurological quirks, and rare deep
    attainments can leave overlapping first-person signatures. Naming is not
    knowing. The mind prefers a dramatic label because drama feels like
    understanding.
  </p>

  <p>
    The canon does name refined cessations. The discourses speak of the
    cessation of perception and feeling —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="saññā-vedayita-nirodha" data-en="cessation of perception and feeling">saññā-vedayita-nirodha</span>
    — as an advanced attainment entered and left by those far along the path, not
    as a casual blank that appears in early concentration. Commentarial maps also
    speak of fruition moments and other interruptions. Those maps can reduce panic
    when held as provisional language. They become trouble when every gap is
    forced into a stage chart. Description first. Diagnosis last — if at all.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Not Nibbāna by Default</h2>

  <p>
    The common overclaim is almost automatic: if consciousness stopped, the
    unconditioned must have shown itself. That confuses a conditioned interruption
    with what the texts place outside the pattern of arising and ceasing.
    <a href="/concepts/nibbana/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation; the unconditioned">Nibbāna</span></a>
    is not a nicer blank. It is named
    <span class="pali" data-pali="asaṅkhata" data-en="unconditioned">asaṅkhata</span>
    — unconditioned — and described primarily as the ending of greed, hatred, and
    delusion, not as a trophy discontinuity in the stream of experience.
  </p>

  <p>
    Peak stillness shares the same category error from another angle. The
    <a href="/concepts/jhanas/"><span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhānas</span></a>
    arise and pass. Formless absorptions refine the object until almost nothing is
    left to track — and remain conditioned, impermanent, unable by themselves to
    uproot the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="āsavā" data-en="taints; fermentations">āsavas</span>.
    A gap can feel more radical than jhāna because there is no afterglow to
    admire. Feeling radical is still a feeling that arises after the fact. It does
    not certify liberation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course some traditions treat certain cessations as decisive insight into the
    unconditioned. That reading deserves respect as a live map — and still deserves
    the raft warning. Even a true teaching becomes harmful when grasped as identity.
    If a gap rearranges how craving and ownership are seen afterward, take the
    rearrangement seriously. If the mind only acquires a new story about having
    touched the Absolute, take the story lightly.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      Monks, I will teach you the Dhamma compared to a raft: for crossing over,
      not for holding on to.
    </p>
    <cite>— MN 22 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <hr>

  <h2>Not a Trophy</h2>

  <p>
    The second mistake arrives almost as quickly as the first. The person who had
    the gap becomes “someone who had X.” Practice turns into hunting a repeat.
    Comparison with others’ maps hardens. Ordinary sits feel like failure because
    they do not reproduce the hole in time. This is the same pattern
    <a href="/concepts/insight-cycles/">insight cycles</a>
    describe after any vivid shift: capture instead of integration.
  </p>

  <p>
    Wanting the gap again is still wanting — pleasant contact of a rarer kind.
    The mind that used to chase calm now chases discontinuity. Both are
    <span class="pali" data-pali="taṇhā" data-en="craving">taṇhā</span>
    wearing contemplative clothes. And the identity move is subtler still: ownership
    relocates from “I am anxious” to “I am one who tasted cessation.” The costume
    changed. The owner did not clock out.
  </p>

  <p>
    So the seal is blunt. A temporary interruption of ordinary consciousness is not
    a credential. It is a front that passed through a conditioned stream.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Helps Afterward</h2>

  <p>
    Useful responses are almost boring — which is why they work. Return to the
    body: posture, breath, contact with the ground. Resume ordinary
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness; recollection">sati</span>
    with whatever is present, including residual awe or disappointment. Keep
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sīla" data-en="virtue; ethical conduct">sīla</span>
    from collapsing under spiritual excitement. Do not build a cosmology from one
    event. Do not announce a stage. Do not quit training because the souvenir was
    impressive. The water, in the Buddha’s hindrance similes, becomes clear when
    conditions settle — not when the mind clutches at a remembered clarity.
  </p>

  <p>
    The test that matters is downstream. Does greed tighten or loosen in speech and
    taking? Does ill-will find less fuel? Does the assumption of a fixed owner show
    up as assumption rather than as destiny? Those questions belong to waking life
    among dishes, deadlines, and fatigue — not only to the memory of a blank.
    Whatever liberation means in the texts, it cannot be a private souvenir that
    collapses the moment ordinary sights and thoughts return.
  </p>

  <p>
    Whether ultimate claims about the unconditioned are finally true or not, living
    as if intentional action and clear seeing matter — as if clinging has
    consequences worth interrupting — still shapes this life. A gap does not exempt
    anyone from that work. It sometimes clarifies why the work was never about
    collecting blanks.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>When to Seek Guidance</h2>

  <p>
    Most gap experiences settle with time, ethics, and continued ordinary practice.
    Some do not. Persistent fear, obsession with repeating the state, dissociation
    that impairs ordinary functioning, sleep collapse, or a sudden conviction of
    special destiny are signals to talk with a trusted teacher or clinician — not
    to diagnose oneself from a book. Maps help when they reduce panic. They harm
    when they become the new owner of attention.
  </p>

  <p>
    Humility about maps is not anti-intellectual. It is recognition that first-person
    discontinuity is easy to over-interpret and hard to verify. The canon’s own
    care around unanswered questions is a model here: some inquiries do not serve
    the ending of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>.
    Building a personal religion out of one blank usually falls in that category.
  </p>

  <p>
    What remains, after the story thins, is simpler. Keep training. Meet what
    arises. Let rare interruptions be rare — known without being worshipped.
  </p>

</article>
